<div class="container">
    <h1>LLM Speedrun Submission Summary</h1>
    <p>This document summarizes the development run logs, engineering choices, and final architecture implemented for the 2,000-step LLM optimization task.</p>

    <h2>1. Final Model Architecture</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Parameters:</strong> 1,673,856 <span class="badge">PASSED CAP (&lt; 2M)</span></li>
        <li><strong>Layers (n_layer):</strong> 6</li>
        <li><strong>Heads (n_head):</strong> 6</li>
        <li><strong>Embedding Size (n_embd):</strong> 192</li>
        <li><strong>Weight Tying:</strong> Enabled (tie_weights = True)</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>2. Key Optimization Improvements</h2>
    <div class="metric-box">
        <strong>Major Enhancements:</strong>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>AdamW Optimizer & Weight Decay:</strong> Added L2 regularization to prevent weight drift on dense text data.</li>
            <li><strong>Warmup & Cosine LR Schedule:</strong> Linear warmup over 200 steps protects initialization; Cosine decay smoothly scales learning down to zero.</li>
            <li><strong>Gradient Clipping:</strong> Hard cap at 1.0 prevents exploding updates on CPU.</li>
            <li><strong>Batch Scaling:</strong> Increased batch size from 8 to 32 for cleaner descent trajectories.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>3. Collaboration & Human-Machine Split</h2>
    <p>The engineering process was a collaborative effort between the developer and a coding agent:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Machine Contribution (60%):</strong> Explored mathematically compatible network configurations, drafted PyTorch structural adjustments, and calculated param bounds automatically.</li>
        <li><strong>Human Contribution (40%):</strong> Identified execution constraints, resolved WSL-to-Windows pathing conflicts, executed terminal run procedures, and completed validation diagnostics.</li>
    </ul>
